Let the phase-space dimension be \(d\) and cover the space with congruent hypercubes \(C_i(\varepsilon)\) of side length \(\varepsilon\) centred at \(x_i\).
For each cell, approximate the enclosed probability to first order in space by Taylor-expanding the phase-space density \(\rho\):

\[
p_i(\varepsilon)
=\int_{C_i(\varepsilon)}\rho(x)\,d^dx
\;\approx\;
\rho(x_i)\,\varepsilon^{d}
\;+\;
\varepsilon^{d+1}\,\mathbf{n}_i\!\cdot\!\nabla\rho(x_i)
\;+\;\mathcal O(\varepsilon^{\,d+2}),
\qquad
\mathbf{n}_i
:=\varepsilon^{-(d+1)}
\!\!\int_{C_i(\varepsilon)}\!(x-x_i)\,d^dx .
\]

Using these coarse-grained probabilities, the Rényi (generalised) dimension of order \(q\neq1\) is defined by

\[
\boxed{
D_q
=\frac{1}{q-1}\,
\lim_{\varepsilon\to 0}
\frac{\displaystyle\log\!\sum_{i}
\left[\rho(x_i)\,\varepsilon^{d}
+\varepsilon^{d+1}\,\mathbf{n}_i\!\cdot\!\nabla\rho(x_i)\right]^{q}}
{\displaystyle\log\varepsilon}}
\]

(The \(\mathbf{n}_i\!\cdot\!\nabla\rho\) term vanishes for symmetric cells, reducing to the familiar \(\rho(x_i)\varepsilon^{d}\) form.)

