\begin{abstract}
Continuous cellular automata (CCAs) have evolved from discrete lookup tables to continuous partial differential equation (PDE) formulations in the search for novel forms of complexity. Despite innovations in qualitative behaviour, analytical methods have lagged behind, reinforcing the notion that emergent complexity defies simple explanation. We demonstrate that the PDE formulation of Asymptotic Lenia enables rigorous analysis using dynamical-systems theory. Employing concepts such as symmetries, attractors, Lyapunov exponents, and fractal dimensions, we mathematically characterise Asymptotic Lenia’s rich behaviours. Our contributions include: (1) a mathematical explanation for the four distinct solution classes (solitons, rotators, periodic patterns, and chaotic patterns); (2) conditions guaranteeing the existence of a global attractor with fractal dimension $>4$; (3) identification of the Kaplan–Yorke dimension as an effective complexity measure for CCAs; and (4) an efficient open-source implementation for computing Lyapunov exponents and covariant Lyapunov vectors in CCAs. We conclude by isolating the minimal set of properties that enable complex behaviour in a broader family of CCAs. This framework provides a foundation for understanding and measuring complexity in artificial-life systems.
