\section{Background}\label{sec:background}

\subsection{Continuous Cellular Automata}

\begin{figure}[ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figs/zoo.png}
    \caption{Four classes of dynamic solutions to Asymptotic Lenia, each existing in a distinct region of the PDE’s parameter space. The \emph{soliton} is a stable, purely translating solution. The \emph{rotator} is a stable, purely rotating solution. The \emph{periodic soliton} both translates and oscillates periodically. The \emph{chaotic soliton} combines translations, rotations, and internal oscillations chaotically.}
    \label{fig:lenia_zoo}
\end{figure}

Continuous cellular automata were first proposed to recreate the complex emergent behaviour of Conway’s Game of Life \citep{Gardner1970} and to discover more life-like patterns. In the pursuit of complexity, CAs gradually evolved into a fully non-local PDE formulation. \emph{Larger-than-Life} \citep{Evans2001} enlarged the kernel, \emph{SmoothLife} \citep{Rafler2011} introduced continuous states, \emph{Lenia} \citep{Chan2019} introduced continuous time and space, and finally \emph{Asymptotic Lenia} \citep{alenia2021} removed the discontinuous update rule. Despite this transition from lookup tables to PDEs, analytical tools for these systems remain under-developed, perpetuating the intuition that emergent complexity resists simple causal explanation.

Here we show that adopting a PDE model permits the import of well-established concepts from dynamical-systems theory. After introducing the requisite ideas—symmetries, attractors, Lyapunov exponents, and fractal dimensions—we provide a mathematical explanation for the observed complexity in Asymptotic Lenia. We then measure these quantities, obtaining a comprehensive characterisation of the system’s solutions. Finally, we propose a practical complexity metric for CCAs and summarise a concise set of key properties sufficient for complex behaviour across a broader class of CCAs.

\subsection{Asymptotic Lenia}

Our analysis focuses on Asymptotic Lenia, currently the only CCA formulated explicitly as a continuous PDE \citep{Davis2022,Kojima2023}. The main classes of dynamic solutions are illustrated in \cref{fig:lenia_zoo}. The PDE is defined by \citet{alenia2021} as
\begin{equation}
    \partial_t A(\mathbf{x},t) = \mathbf{F}(A, K*A) = T(K*A) - A,\label{asymptotic_lenia}
\end{equation}
where $A \colon \mathbb{R}^{2}\!\times\!\mathbb{R}^{+} \to \mathbb{R}$ is a real-valued scalar field, $K \colon \mathbb{R}^{2} \to \mathbb{R}$ is a radially symmetric kernel, $(*)$ denotes 2-D convolution, and $T \colon \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$ is the growth function applied pointwise. The Gaussian growth function $T(u)=\exp\bigl[-\tfrac12(u-\mu)^{2}/\sigma^{2}\bigr]$ is parameterised by $0<\sigma\ll\mu$ and is typically approximated by a polynomial or step function for computational efficiency. The kernel $K(\mathbf{x})=K(\|\mathbf{x}\|_2)$ is a sum of uniformly spaced concentric rings of the form $K_C(r) = \bigl(4r(r-1)\bigr)^{4}$, with parameters $\{\beta_i\}$ controlling the ring amplitudes and $R$ setting the overall spatial scale. Crucially, $K(0)=0$, and $K$ is normalised so that $\int_{\Omega} K(\mathbf{x})\,\mathrm{d}\mathbf{x}=1$. We assume the PDE is solved on a bounded domain $\Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^{2}$ with periodic boundary conditions.

We also consider the spatially discretised version of Asymptotic Lenia, yielding a finite-dimensional ODE system that mirrors practical numerical implementations. At each grid point $(i,j)\in[0,N-1]^{2}$ we define the time-dependent variable $A[i,j](t)\in\mathbb{R}$. The dynamics are
\begin{equation}
    \frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}t}A[i,j](t)=\mathbf{F}[i,j](A)=T\bigl((K*A)[i,j]\bigr)-A[i,j].\label{discrete_asymptotic_lenia}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Dynamical Systems}

To analyse Asymptotic Lenia we employ the framework of dynamical systems for fields—functions of space—evolving through time. Although a fully rigorous infinite-dimensional treatment lies beyond the scope of this paper, we restrict attention to the finite-dimensional setting without sacrificing generality. One key concept borrowed from the infinite-dimensional theory is \emph{symmetry}.

A \emph{symmetry group} of a system of differential equations is a group of transformations that maps solutions to solutions \citep{Olver1986}. When the transformation depends on a continuous parameter (e.g. translation by $\delta$ in the $x$-direction), the symmetry is \emph{continuous}. Continuous symmetries form a \emph{Lie group}. For example, the plane’s rotations and translations constitute the Lie group $SE(2)$. The corresponding infinitesimal transformations form the \emph{Lie algebra}, whose elements are the \emph{generators} of the group—for instance, $\partial_x$ and $\partial_y$ generate planar translations, while $x\partial_y-y\partial_x$ generates rotations. All two-dimensional CCAs are invariant under $SE(2)$ because their update rules are spatially homogeneous and depend only on radial distance; they are also invariant under time translation because the rule is autonomous.

We now recast the finite-dimensional theory in the language of \citet[e.g.][]{Temam1997,Hale1988,Robinson2001,Sell2002}, mapping each definition onto discretised Asymptotic Lenia:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Phase space} $\mathcal{X}=\mathbb{R}^{N^{2}}$: the set of all possible states.
    \item \textbf{Evolution law} $\dot A(t)=\mathbf{F}(A)$: the ODE system governing temporal evolution.
    \item \textbf{Semiflow} $\Phi_t\bigl(A(0)\bigr)=A(t)$, $t\ge0$: maps an initial state to its future state. Existence follows because $\mathbf{F}$ is Lipschitz and $|A|$ cannot blow up in finite time \citep{Robinson2001}\footnote{The Lipschitz property follows from the boundedness of $K*A$ and Lipschitz continuity of $T$. The norm $|A|$ is bounded because it can grow or decay at most exponentially.}.
\end{itemize}

The following properties then apply.
\paragraph{Dissipativity.} A semiflow $\Phi_t$ on $\mathbb{R}^{n}$ is \emph{dissipative} if there exists a bounded set $\mathcal{B}\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}$ that absorbs every trajectory in finite time.

\paragraph{Global attractor.} If $\Phi_t$ is dissipative, there exists a \emph{global attractor} $\mathcal{A}$—the minimal set toward which all trajectories converge as $t\to\infty$. The attractor encapsulates all long-term dynamics and supports at least one invariant measure.

\paragraph{Fractal dimension.} Dissipative chaotic systems settle onto attractors of zero phase-space volume that cannot be represented by integer-dimensional manifolds. Such \emph{fractal attractors} are characterised by their fractal dimension. We focus on the generalised dimensions \citep{Grassberger1983}
\begin{equation*}
    D_q = \frac{1}{1-q}\lim_{\varepsilon\to0}\frac{\log \bigl(\sum_i p_i^{q}\bigr)}{\log (1/\varepsilon)},
\end{equation*}
where $p_i$ is the mass in the $i$-th box of a uniform phase-space partition of size $\varepsilon$. $D_0$ is the \emph{box-counting} dimension, $D_1$ the \emph{information} dimension, and $D_2$ the \emph{correlation} dimension; they coincide only when the invariant density is uniform.

\paragraph{Lyapunov exponents.} The Lyapunov exponents (LEs) $\{\lambda_i\}_{i=1}^{n}$ of a trajectory $A(t)$ are the average exponential growth rates of perturbations to $A(0)$. A positive exponent signals chaos because nearby trajectories diverge exponentially. Among several equivalent definitions (see \citet[Sec.~6.3.1]{Kuznetsov2020}), the most convenient here is
\[
    \lambda_i\bigl(A(0)\bigr)=\limsup_{t\to\infty}\frac{1}{t}\log \sigma_i\bigl(A(0),t\bigr),
\]
where $\sigma_i$ is the $i$-th largest singular value of the Jacobian $\nabla_A\Phi_t$. These exponents can be approximated numerically via the algorithm of \citet{Benettin1980}. Covariant Lyapunov vectors (CLVs), giving the associated perturbation directions, follow from a short backward pass \citep{Ginelli2007}.

\paragraph{Kaplan–Yorke dimension.} The Kaplan–Yorke dimension $D_{KY}$ provides a heuristic upper bound on $D_1$ and often matches it closely \citep{Groger2013}:
\[
    D_{KY}=j+\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{j}\lambda_i}{|\lambda_{j+1}|},
\]
where $j$ is the largest index for which the cumulative sum of the $j$ largest exponents is non-negative.

\section{Mathematical Results}
\subsection{Existence of Symmetry Solutions}

Equation~\eqref{asymptotic_lenia} is invariant under the group $G=SE(2)\times\mathbb{R}$. The corresponding Lie algebra is
\[
    \mathfrak g=\operatorname{span}_{\mathbb R}\{\partial_x,\;\partial_y,\;x\partial_y-y\partial_x,\;\partial_t\}.
\]
Using these symmetries we derive \emph{symmetry solutions}. Employing the ansatz $A(\mathbf{x},t)=e^{t\gamma}A_0$ with $\gamma\in\mathfrak g$ and $A_0=A(\mathbf{x},0)$, we obtain
\begin{align}
    \partial_t\bigl[e^{t\gamma}A_0\bigr] &= \mathbf{F}\bigl(e^{t\gamma}A_0, K*(e^{t\gamma}A_0)\bigr)\nonumber\\
    \gamma e^{t\gamma}A_0 &= \mathbf{F}\bigl(e^{t\gamma}A_0, e^{t\gamma}(K*A_0)\bigr)\nonumber\\
    e^{t\gamma}\gamma A_0 &= e^{t\gamma}\mathbf{F}(A_0,K*A_0)\nonumber\\
    \gamma A_0 &= \mathbf{F}(A_0,K*A_0).\label{stationary_cond}
\end{align}
The third line uses $G$-equivariance of $\mathbf{F}$ and the commutativity of $e^{t\gamma}$ with $\gamma$ and $K$. Condition~\eqref{stationary_cond} means no temporal evolution is needed to verify a symmetry solution. For example, to find a translating solution with velocity $\mathbf{v}$—$A(\mathbf{x},t)=A(\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{v}t,0)$—one seeks $A_0$ satisfying \eqref{stationary_cond} with $\gamma=-\mathbf{v}\cdot[\partial_x\,\partial_y]^\top$. A trivial solution always exists because $\mathbf{F}(\mathbf{0},K*\mathbf{0})=\mathbf{0}$.

\citet[Thm.~2.15]{Aston1994} showed that for $G$-equivariant flows the number of zero Lyapunov exponents equals $\dim G-\dim\{g\in G\mid g\cdot A=A\}$. Hence a purely translating solution has at most $4-1=3$ zero exponents, while a solution fixed by all symmetries has four.

\subsection{Dissipativity and the Global Attractor}

We now establish that all trajectories remain bounded and converge to a common attractor. Following \citet{Robinson2001}, discretised Asymptotic Lenia forms a dissipative semiflow. For $\varepsilon>0$ define $\mathcal{B}_{\varepsilon}=[-\varepsilon,1+\varepsilon]^{N^{2}}\subset\mathcal{X}$. Let $m(t)=\min_{i,j}A[i,j](t)$ and $M(t)=\max_{i,j}A[i,j](t)$. Assuming $0\le T(\cdot)\le1$ and starting from any $A[i,j](0)\in\mathcal{X}$,
\begin{align*}
    \frac{\mathrm{d}M}{\mathrm{d}t} &= T\bigl((K*A)[i_M,j_M]\bigr)-M \le 1-M,\\[4pt]
    &\Rightarrow M(t)\le1+\bigl(M(0)-1\bigr)e^{-t},\\[8pt]
    \frac{\mathrm{d}m}{\mathrm{d}t} &= T\bigl((K*A)[i_m,j_m]\bigr)-m \ge -m,\\[4pt]
    &\Rightarrow m(t)\ge m(0)e^{-t},
\end{align*}
where $(i_M,j_M)$ and $(i_m,j_m)$ index the maximum and minimum values. After
\[
    t^{*}=\max\Bigl\{\ln\Bigl|\tfrac{M(0)-1}{\varepsilon}\Bigr|,\;\ln\Bigl|\tfrac{m(0)}{\varepsilon}\Bigr|\Bigr\},
\]
all trajectories lie in $\mathcal{B}_{\varepsilon}$ for $t\ge t^{*}$. Hence a global attractor $\mathcal{A}$ exists. A parallel argument applies to the continuous PDE, but is omitted.

\subsection{Helmholtz Decomposition and Dynamics on the Attractor}

To understand why Asymptotic Lenia supports complex behaviour, we decompose its vector field into divergence-free and gradient parts via the Helmholtz–Hodge theorem \citep{hhd2013}. Computing the Jacobian of \eqref{discrete_asymptotic_lenia} yields
\begin{align*}
    \frac{\partial \mathbf{F}[i,j](A)}{\partial A[k,l]} &= T'\bigl((K*A)[i,j]\bigr)\,K[i-k,j-l]-\delta_{ik}\delta_{jl}.
\end{align*}
Setting $K[0,0]=0$ makes the first term divergence-free; summing the Kronecker deltas gives $\nabla_A\!\cdot\mathbf{F}=-N^{2}$. Thus
\[
    \mathbf{F}[i,j](A)=\underbrace{T\bigl((K*A)[i,j]\bigr)}_{\text{divergence-free}}+\underbrace{\frac{\partial}{\partial A[i,j]}\Bigl[-\tfrac12\sum_{k,l}A^{2}[k,l]\Bigr]}_{\text{gradient}}.
\]
Because $\mathbf{F}$ is not a pure gradient field, trajectories need not approach fixed points and can settle onto dynamic attractors. This decomposition clarifies why classic “neighbour-sum plus non-linearity” rules support periodic and chaotic motions.

\begin{figure*}[ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figs/lyap.png}
    \caption{Lyapunov spectra for the four solution classes of \cref{fig:lenia_zoo}. Left: the ten largest exponents. Right: convergence of those exponents over time. Kaplan–Yorke dimensions computed from the converged spectra appear in the titles.}
    \label{fig:lyap_spectrum}
\end{figure*}

\begin{figure*}[ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figs/clv.png}
    \caption{Covariant Lyapunov vectors (CLVs) for the chaotic soliton. Left: field after 90,000 steps ($\Delta t=0.1$). Right: the ten leading CLVs; blue denotes negative and red positive components.}
    \label{fig:clv}
\end{figure*}

\section{Experimental Results}

With the theoretical framework in place, we measure key quantities to characterise each solution class. Theory predicts that chaotic solutions possess a global attractor whose fractal dimension lies between 4 and $N^{2}$, reflecting systemic complexity. We verify this by computing LEs and the Kaplan–Yorke dimension for representative solutions from \cref{fig:lenia_zoo}.

LEs are obtained for the discretised flow using the algorithm of \citet{Benettin1980}. We integrate $k$ orthogonal tangent vectors $\mathbf{v}_{i}$ via $\dot{\mathbf{v}}_{i}=\nabla_A\mathbf{F}\,\mathbf{v}_{i}$ and periodically apply QR decomposition to maintain orthogonality. The time-averaged logarithmic growth of $\|\mathbf{v}_{i}\|$ yields the $k$ largest exponents, which feed into the Kaplan–Yorke formula.

Spectra for the four solution classes appear in \cref{fig:lyap_spectrum}. Simulations use $N=256$ and $\Delta t=0.1$. After discarding transients, we perform a 100,000-step forward pass and a 10,000-step backward pass, averaging the last 50,000 steps to estimate finite-time LEs.

As expected, purely rotating and translating solutions have three zero exponents, whereas periodic and chaotic solutions have four. For non-chaotic classes the largest exponents are effectively zero, so $D_{KY}$ equals the number of zero exponents (we set $|\lambda_i|<10^{-3}$ to zero). The chaotic soliton exhibits two significant positive exponents and $D_{KY}\approx8.46$.

The spectra explain the system’s robustness to perturbations: all but a handful of the $N^{2}$ exponents are negative (mean $-1$), so most perturbation modes decay exponentially. \cref{fig:clv} visualises unstable, neutral, and stable directions via the CLVs of the chaotic soliton. Within the neutral set, $\lambda_{4}$ and $\lambda_{6}$ share nearly identical CLVs, reflecting a degenerate subspace \citep{Ginelli2013}.

\section{Discussion}

The computations confirm theory: zero exponents match symmetry predictions, and chaotic patterns possess at least one positive exponent with $D_{KY}>4$. Lyapunov analysis is computationally inexpensive and interpretable compared with traditional fractal-dimension estimators.

\subsection{Kaplan–Yorke Dimension as a Complexity Measure}
Box-counting dimension is impractical for finely discretised PDEs, and correlation dimension converges slowly because it relies on sampling the heavy tail of pairwise distances. By contrast, Kaplan–Yorke dimension requires only Jacobian–vector products and QR decompositions at each time step. Even for chaotic attractors, we achieve $<1\%$ error after roughly $10^{4}$ steps at $\Delta t=0.1$.

Because $D_{KY}$ upper-bounds the information dimension, it answers the intuitive question: \emph{how many real numbers are needed to specify a state on the attractor at a given resolution?} We therefore recommend $D_{KY}$ as a practical complexity metric for continuous and neural cellular automata.

\subsection{Generalising CCAs}
\cref{tab:assumptions} summarises the mathematical predictions and the minimal assumptions underlying them.

\begin{table}[h]
    \centering
    \begin{tabular}{p{0.42\linewidth}p{0.48\linewidth}}
        \toprule
        \textbf{Assumption} & \textbf{Prediction}\\
        \midrule
        $\partial_tA=T(K*A)-A$,\quad $K$ radially symmetric & Symmetry solutions and up to four zero Lyapunov exponents.\\
        \midrule
        $0\le T(\cdot)\le1$, $T$ Lipschitz & Existence of a global attractor.\\
        \midrule
        $K[0,0]=0$ & $\dim\mathcal{A}<N^{2}$; flow is not a pure gradient, allowing dynamic attractors.\\
        \bottomrule
    \end{tabular}
    \caption{Key assumptions and their implications for Asymptotic Lenia dynamics.}
    \label{tab:assumptions}
\end{table}

These assumptions do not guarantee chaos, but Asymptotic Lenia shows that suitable $T$ and $K$ satisfying them can produce chaotic attractors. Nevertheless, Asymptotic Lenia explores only a low-dimensional subset of all such functions.

To seek richer phenomena—including replication and goal-directedness—we propose studying the broader class
\begin{equation}
    \partial_tA(\mathbf{x},t)=f(K*A)-\nabla_A G(A),
\end{equation}
where $K$ is bounded, radially symmetric, and satisfies $K(0)=0$; $f$ is Lipschitz with $0\le f\le1$; and $G$ is convex with no minimisers outside $[0,1]^{N^{2}}$ and $\nabla_A G(\mathbf{1})\ge\mathbf{1}$. These conditions ensure dissipativity and non-positive, spatially varying divergence, which may yield highly multifractal attractors and new forms of complexity.

\section{Conclusion}

We have shown that dynamical-systems theory provides rigorous tools for analysing Asymptotic Lenia and, by extension, a broad family of CCAs. By computing Lyapunov spectra and fractal dimensions with an open-source implementation, we experimentally verified that a small set of properties suffices for chaotic behaviour. Extending this framework could illuminate replication, reproduction, and goal-directedness in artificial-life models. We encourage future work on continuous-time neural cellular automata to quantify complexity using the Lyapunov analysis outlined here.

